<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<h3>Is edible gold leaf real gold?</h3>
<p>Yes — food-grade gold leaf is 22–24 carat gold, applied in extremely thin sheets. It is inert and safe to eat in the tiny quantities used on cakes.</p>
<h3>How much does gold leaf add to the price of a cake?</h3>
<p>A single gold-leaf accent typically adds $15–40 to a cake. Full gold tiers add more, both in materials and labour.</p>
<h3>Can I use fake gold spray instead?</h3>
<p>Some sprays are labelled ''non-toxic'' but not ''edible''. Always confirm with your baker that any metallic is food-safe.</p>
<h3>Do gold cakes photograph well in low light?</h3>
<p>Yes — gold catches ambient light better than any other cake finish, which is why it dominates event photography.</p>
<h3>Is gold too formal for a birthday cake?</h3>
<p>Not if used sparingly. A single gold accent on an otherwise casual cake reads as considered, not stuffy.</p>

